iv></div></div></div></div>\n</div>\n</article></main></article>\n</div></div></div><div class=\"bottomFeedback\"><div aria-labelledby=\"bottomFeedbackText\" class=\"bottomFeedbackContent\" role=\"group\"><span class=\"bottomFeedbackText\" id=\"bottomFeedbackText\">Was this topic helpful?</span><div class=\"bottomFeedbackButtonGroup\"><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_2530625\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-up\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-up\"></use></svg><span>Like</span></a><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_2530625\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-down\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-down\"></use></svg><span>Dislike</span></a></div></div></div><div style=\"position: fixed; bottom: 170px; right: 70px; cursor: pointer; transition-duration: 0.2s; transition-timing-function: linear; transition-delay: 0s; z-index: 3; opacity: 0; visibility: hidden; transition-property: opacity, visibility;\"><button aria-label=\"Scroll to top\" class=\"zDocsScrollTopBtn\" data-tooltip-content=\"Scroll to top\" data-tooltip-id=\"zDocsBackToTopToolTip\" id=\"zDocsScrollToTop\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-next\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-next\"></use></svg></button></div></body></html>", "text": "Mnemonics for Nonprintable ASCII Add to My Topics Add selected topic and subtopics Add Topic & Subtopics with topic head Add entire publication Watch Download PDF Save selected topic Save selected topic and subtopics Save entire publication Share Email Link Copy Link Feedback Last Updated Okt 13, 2022 Summarize Uniface 10.4 Mnemonics for Nonprintable ASCII The control codes required by devices and function key sequences on keyboards often contain nonprintable ASCII characters (with values between 0 and 32 decimal) such as ^ESC, ^SOH, ^NUL, and so on. The translation table compiler recognizes special mnemonics for nonprintable ASCII characters. When a non-alphanumeric code (such as clear_screen ) is sent to an output device, it expects to receive control codes that represent this function. When a nonalphanumeric key, such as PF1, is pressed, the keyboard sends out a sequence of codes that represent this key. The documentation that is supplied with the device or keyboard should list the control codes or keyboard code required for these special functions and keys. Uniface ignores the case of the mnemonics, that is, uppercase and lowercase are equivalent. An optional single caret (^) can be used in front of a mnemonic to improve the readability of a device translation table. Search: Column Mnemonic Decimal value Octal value ASCII character Filter results... 33 rows found Export to Excel Export to CSV Table 1. Mnemonics for Non-Printable ASCII Characters Mnemonic Decimal value Octal value ASCII character Filter 33 rows found Filter 33 rows found Filter 33 rows found Filter 33 rows found Mnemonic Decimal value Octal value ASCII character ^NUL ^0 ^/0 NULL. ^SOH ^1 ^/1 Start of heading. ^STX ^2 ^/2 Start of text. ^ETX ^3 ^/3 End of text. ^EOT ^4 ^/4 End of transmission. ^ENQ ^5 ^/5 Enquiry. ^ACK ^6 ^/6 Acknowledge. ^BEL ^7 ^/7 Bell (audible signal). ^BS ^8 ^/10 Backspace. ^HT ^9 ^/11 Horizontal tab. ^LF ^10 ^/12 Line feed. ^VT ^11 ^/13 Vertical tab. ^FF ^12 ^/14 Form feed. ^CR ^13 ^/15 Carriage return. ^SO ^14 ^/16 Shift out. ^SI ^15 ^/17 Shift in. ^DLE ^16 ^/20 Data link escape. ^DC1 ^17 ^/21 Device control 1. ^DC2 ^18 ^/22 Device control 2. ^DC3 ^19 ^/23 Device control 3. ^DC4 ^20 ^/24 Device control 4 (stop). ^NAK ^21 ^/25 Negative acknowledge. ^SYN ^22 ^/26 Synchronous idle. ^ETB ^23 ^/27 End of transmission block. ^CAN ^24 ^/30 Cancel. ^EM ^25 ^/31 End of medium. ^SUB ^26 ^/32 Substitute. ^ESC ^27 ^/33 Escape. ^FS ^28 ^/34 File separator. ^GS ^29 ^/35 Group separator. ^RS ^30 ^/36 Record separator. ^US ^31 ^/37 Unit separator. ^SP ^32 ^/40 Blank space. Was this topic helpful? Like Dislike"}